## Qaap project information

Qaap is a product fork of Eclipse Theia, a TypeScript framework for building IDEs. This repository is a Lerna-managed monorepo of ~80 packages. You are an autonomous CLI coding agent working inside a checkout of it — there is no IDE around you, so ignore any advice about launch configurations, debug profiles, or in-IDE "tasks": run the shell commands below directly.

### Most important rule: upstream-drift policy

All new Qaap product code MUST live under `packages/qaap-*`. Do NOT modify files inside upstream Theia packages (any `packages/<name>` where `<name>` does not start with `qaap-`). CI enforces this with `node scripts/qaap-drift-check.js`: every changed file must be inside `packages/qaap-*`, matched by an `ALLOWED` regex (with a comment), or baselined — otherwise the build fails.

When a behaviour needs an upstream file changed, extract instead of editing it in place:
- Preference default → new `PreferenceContribution` in a `qaap-*` package.
- Service / widget behaviour → subclass the upstream class in `qaap-*` and `rebind(Upstream).to(QaapSubclass)` in the frontend module.
- Contribution (menu / keybinding / command) → add a new contribution in `qaap-*`; never edit the upstream one.
- CSS rule → add it to a `qaap-product-theme` stylesheet and import it from that package's frontend module.
- Branding string → use `FrontendApplicationConfigProvider.applicationName`; never hardcode "Theia".

### Layout

- `packages/` — runtime packages: upstream Theia extensions plus the Qaap product layer (`qaap-*`).
- `dev-packages/` — build tooling (cli, application-manager, ext-scripts).
- `examples/` — sample apps; the browser example is what you build and run.
- Per package, platform folders enforce dependency direction: `src/common` (shared), `src/browser` (frontend, Inversify DI), `src/node` (backend, Inversify DI), `src/electron-*`. Browser code must not import node code.

Components are wired with dependency injection (Inversify); a contributed class is bound in its package's frontend or backend module. Prefer property injection and `@postConstruct()` over constructor injection. Use a `ContributionProvider` (bound via `bindRootContributionProvider`) instead of `@multiInject` to collect multiple implementations.

### Build, verify, run

Run everything from the repo root with `npm` (not yarn). Never run `.ts` source directly — packages import each other's compiled `lib/` output, so always compile first.

- Compile TypeScript: `npm run compile`
- Check the drift policy: `node scripts/qaap-drift-check.js`
- Bundle the browser app (required before any UI check): `npm run build:browser`
- Start the app: `npm run start:browser` (serves http://localhost:3000)
- Lint: `npm run lint` (auto-fix: `npm run lint:fix`)
- Run all tests: `npm run test`
- One package: `npx lerna run <compile|test> --scope @theia/<package>`
- One compiled test file: `npx mocha ./packages/<pkg>/lib/<path>/<file>.spec.js`

Standard verify sequence after a code change: `npm run compile` → `node scripts/qaap-drift-check.js` → `npm run build:browser` (only when UI needs checking in the browser). Note: `build:browser` bundles the frontend only and does NOT reload an already-running server — restart `start:browser` after any `src/node` (backend) change.

### Conventions

- 4-space indent, single quotes, `undefined` (never `null`), explicit return types, arrow functions.
- PascalCase for types/enums; camelCase for functions/variables; kebab-case file names matching the main exported type.
- No `I` prefix on interfaces; prefer a class over an interface + symbol when possible.
- Localize user-facing strings: `nls.localizeByDefault('Close')` when the string exists in VS Code's language packs, otherwise `nls.localize('theia/<package>/<id>', 'text', ...args)`.
- Pass URIs (as strings) across frontend/backend, never raw paths; manipulate paths with `URI`/`Path`, not string concatenation.
- No hardcoded colors or inline styles in code: register colors via `ColorContribution` and reference VS Code theme colors in CSS as `var(--theia-...)`.
- In React, don't bind functions in event handlers; use class-property arrow functions.

### Qaap product contract (critical)

Work Hub is the default surface after every browser reload, on mobile and desktop. The classic IDE may open only after an explicit in-runtime "Open IDE" action, and that choice must never survive reload/F5 — do not persist a desktop-IDE preference in `sessionStorage`, `localStorage`, URL state, or restored layout.

### Tests

`*.spec.ts` (unit), `*.ui-spec.ts` (UI), `*.slow-spec.ts` (slow). Tests live beside the code under test and must be compiled before running. Example backend test: `packages/core/src/common/content-replacer.spec.ts`. Example frontend test: `packages/ai-code-completion/src/browser/code-completion-postprocessor.spec.ts`.

